{"questionId":"26495","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A company produces bags of sugar with a labelled weight of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math>. The weights of the bags are&nbsp;normally distributed with a mean of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>kg</mtext></math> and a standard deviation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>g</mtext></math>. In an inspection, if&nbsp;the weight of a randomly chosen bag is less than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>950</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>g</mtext></math> then the company fails the inspection.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>A statistician in the company suggests it would be fairer if the company passes the inspection&nbsp;when the mean weight of five randomly chosen bags is greater than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>950</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>g</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the probability of passing the inspection if the statistician’s suggestion is followed.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>X</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></math>&nbsp;be the mean weight of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> bags of sugar</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext><mfenced><mover><mi>X</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>use of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Var</mtext><mfenced><mover><mi>X</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>σ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Var</mtext><mfe